"{\"Wiki\": \"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clerodendrum_splendens\", \"Bark Color\": \"grey brown\", \"Where\": [\"100ft Road, 6 Main Road, II Stage, Indiranagar, Bangalore\"], \"Common Family\": \"verbena\", \"Name\": \"Flaming Glorybower\", \"Family\": \"Verbenaceae\", \"Leaves Type\": \"ovate\", \"Flowers Color\": \"scarlet\", \"Grow Type\": \"Evergreen\", \"Links\": [\"http://www.flowersofindia.in/catalog/slides/Flaming%20Glorybower.html\"], \"Authority\": \"G. Don\", \"Description\": \"Flaming glorybower, native to western Africa, is a woody or semi-woody evergreen vine or running shrub to 12 ft long, that climbs by twining. The leaves are oval, to 7 in long, and arranged in opposite pairs. Flowers are tuba shaped, having a slender tube with an abruptly expanded corolla. They are scarlet (sometimes white), about 1 in across and borne in dense terminal clusters to 5 in inches long. The fruit is unknown. This evergreen climber is popular in warm, humid climates and can be used as an evergreen screen on a trellis or wall. The flowers are extremely showy and attractive to butterflies as well as people. Flaming glory bower can be found growing up the pillars and walls and exhibits its peak flowering during December and January.\", \"Fruits Texture\": \"unknown\", \"Size\": \"Small\", \"Images\": [\"Flaming Glorybower\", [\"0000\", \"Canopy\", \"Flower Bud\", \"Flower\", \"Leaf\"]], \"Flowers Shape\": \"tuba\", \"Language Common\": \"Flaming Glorybower, Pagoda Flower, Bleeding Heart Vine\", \"Genus\": \"Clerodendrum\", \"Type\": \"Climber\", \"Species\": \"splendens\", \"Native\": \"West Africa\"}"
